node.title: The latest update on our AR Project House!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Atomic Ranch on August 18, 2021. May be an image of nature and tree.

node.text:
Let's zero in on xeriscape. ⁠
This low-water, landscaping style does not have to mean just rocks and cacti, but strategically places plants closer to where you will see and enjoy them.⁠
Jim Coffman, president of Coffman Studio in Tempe, Arizona , shares his expert insight with us . Read his thoughts via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo courtesy of Coffman Studio⁠
⁠

node.text:
Philmer J. Ellerbroek’s personal home in the Tustin foothills of Orange County, California, went on the market last year. After a few different homeowners gave it undesirable makeovers, it lost its charm. However, homeowner Casey Lesher’s dreamed of restoring it to its original beauty. See the stunning result via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo by Chad Mellon @chadmellon⁠
⁠

node.text:
This West Seattle neighborhood consists of bungalows and ‘war boxes’—a somewhat derisive term for boxy postwar tract homes—built between 1955 and 1965. When the homeowners purchased the property in 2008, they had their work cut out for them! Read about their renovation saga via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo by Jim Brown⁠
⁠

node.text:
Grab a seat! Denver's Modernism Week is quickly approaching and is offering fantastic events for high-altitude mod enthusiasts. We spoke with Dana Sednek, co-founder of Denver Modernism Week, about the organization’s vision and the 2021 events. Check it out via the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
Photo courtesy of Denver Modernism Week @denvermodernismweek⁠
⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Atomic Ranch on August 15, 2021. May be an image of tree and outdoors.

node.text:
The exterior of this Maryland home represents the elements that architect Gregory Wiedemann (who oversaw the restoration of this project) loves the most about MCM design: “The simple post-and-beam structure with an iconic low-pitched gabled roof in service of clean horizontal lines that integrate the home with nature.” See more of this Maryland mid century marvel via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
 Photo by Anice Hoachlander⁠
⁠

Looking for inspiration for a living room refresh? This 1960s retro flat has a vibe worth recreating, so we found some mid century modern-inspired decor that will help you achieve a similar look. Take the link in our bio for our picks!⁠
⁠
Image Courtesy of Evening Standard/Getty Images⁠

node.text:
We’re beginning to dream of fall, and with that comes cooler temperatures and more opportunities for cozy moments. You never want to be without a blanket when those moments arise, so we gathered some MCM throws you’ll be happy to display and have on hand. Take the link in our bio to find yourself in the throes of throws!⁠
⁠
Photo by Bret Gum @gum_and_gummer⁠
⁠

node.text:
Does the approaching Autumnal season have you thinking of 🍂branching out🍂 and adding trees to your home's outdoor spaces? Here are some ideas for trees that will look great now and will continue to look great whenever the changing colors arrive. Take the link in our bio for trees that can help boost your MCM curb appeal across the seasons.⁠
⁠
Photo by Daniel Blue @danielbluephotography⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Atomic Ranch on August 12, 2021 tagging @arcsurfaces. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
Creating a showstopper mid mod home requires more than just nice paint and varnish! The secret to unforgettable Mid Century Modern design is making sure the details, like your home’s retro-inspired surfaces, are topnotch. With gorgeous materials sourced from across the globe, Architectural Surfaces is the expert in statement surfaces that endure. Click the tag or the link in our bio to find out more!⁠
#ad #advertisement #theatomicranch #midcenturydesign #midmod #decor #decorinspo #homedesign #ArcSurfaces #ArchitecturalSurfaces⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Atomic Ranch on August 12, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and tree.

node.text:
The legacy of Francis Gassner lives on today through the expressive structures that story the streets of Memphis as well as his namesake award presented yearly by AIA Memphis. But who was the man bodying forth a dynamic vision of Mid Century Modern architecture throughout the post-war 50s and the Civil Rights 60s in Memphis? Find out more via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo by Michael Berry⁠
⁠

node.text:
Delightfully designed in Denver! This Usonian home includes a studio space above the garage. The front yard has been carefully landscaped with plants suited for the high altitude climate including juniper, daylilies, lamb’s ears and bark mulch. Lean more about this home via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo by Jim Brown⁠
⁠
